    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-10-31T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-10-31T13:00:00-05:00" n="29"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d29">
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">No. 29</seg>
                </opener>
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <gloss target="#t_ECA1">ECA</gloss> message files, <gloss target="#t_FRC1"
                        >FRC</gloss> 53A278, Paris: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Acting United States Special Representative in Europe
                        (</hi>
                    <persName corresp="#p_RJW1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Riddleberger</hi>
                    </persName>
                    <hi rend="italic">) to the Acting Administrator for Economic Cooperation (</hi>
                    <persName corresp="#p_BRMJ1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bissell</hi>
                    </persName>
                    <hi rend="italic">)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret   priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-10-31T19:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 31, 1951—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Repto1">Repto</gloss> 5477. For <persName corresp="#p_HWA1"
                        >Harriman</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_BRMJ1">Bissell</persName> and
                        <persName corresp="#p_PPR1">Porter</persName> from Tasca and <persName
                        corresp="#p_GL2">Gordon</persName>. Ref: <gloss target="#t_Torep1"
                        >Torep</gloss> 8159;<note n="1" xml:id="d29fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>.</note>
                    <gloss target="#t_Repto1">Repto</gloss> 5428;<note n="2" xml:id="d29fn2"
                        >Document 27.</note> airgram <gloss target="#t_Repto1">Repto</gloss>
                    circular A–708.<note n="3" xml:id="d29fn3">Not printed.</note> Full text
                    decision <gloss target="#t_OEEC1">OEEC</gloss> council sent Washington via ref
                    airgram. That plus <gloss target="#t_reftel1">reftel</gloss> gives all info
                    available present time. Character of European members will depend in part upon
                    US selection. Role of <persName>Stikker</persName> in coal plus his two advisers
                    for purpose of supplying political tone required. Steel and power require more
                    high level technical appraisal. Would appear feasible to extend
                        <persName>Stikker</persName> approach to steel and power on same basis as
                    coal.</p>
                <p>Do not understand reference to high level admin officials. Believe maximum impact
                    US would be thru highly qualified people from industries concerned. Role of US
                    participants would be to supply technical know-how at high level with particular
                    reference to problems of expansion in sectors involved as well as to underline
                    great US interest in development of concrete expansion targets. Incidentally
                    believe that there should be high level labor participation at all stages.
                    Cruikshank considering problem this end.</p>
                <p>Determination of procedure for manpower clearly linked to arrangements made in
                    other fields. In any case, feel further study necessary on our part to determine
                    objectives and suitable procedures to realize objectives. <gloss
                        target="#t_OSR1">OSR</gloss> Labor Division currently studying this problem.
                    Believe agriculture would be handled by ordinary vertical Food and Agriculture
                    Comite of <gloss target="#t_OEEC1">OEEC</gloss>. Urge strongly that you proceed
                    immed with respect to coal, steel and power as recommended <gloss
                        target="#t_Repto1">Repto</gloss> 5428. Separate comments will follow on
                    manpower and agriculture. [Tasca and <persName corresp="#p_GL2"
                        >Gordon</persName>.]<note n="4" xml:id="d29fn4">No specific reply to
                        telegram <gloss target="#t_Repto1">Repto</gloss> 5477 has been found in
                        Department of State or <gloss target="#t_ECA1">ECA</gloss> message files.
                            <persName corresp="#p_RJW1">Riddleberger</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_PPR1">Porter</persName> began sending detailed reports on
                        the meetings of various <gloss target="#t_OEEC1">OEEC</gloss> committees and
                        special working groups, for example, telegrams <gloss target="#t_Repto1"
                            >Repto</gloss> 5502, November 1, <gloss target="#t_Repto1">Repto</gloss>
                        5627, November 9, <gloss target="#t_Repto1">Repto</gloss> 5734, November 16,
                        and <gloss target="#t_Repto1">Repto</gloss> 5738, November 16, in <gloss
                            target="#t_ECA1">ECA</gloss> message files, <gloss target="#t_FRC1"
                            >FRC</gloss> 53A278, Paris.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Riddleberger</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
